\intbl \ql \b Background\b0 \line The Independent Institute of Education is registered with the Department of Higher Education and Training as a private higher education provider and is accredited to offer higher education programmes by the HEQC.\line \line The Bachelor of Business Administration in Hospitality Management programme was deferred during the Accreditation Committee meeting of 05 and 06 October 2011. The institution was requested to provide clarity on the following\'3A\line \line 1.The programme design has major problems. The designator does not necessarily match the curriculum. The curriculum design exhibits inconsistencies and contradictions with respect to the content of constituent components not being appropriate for the programme purpose. The designator\'2C title and curriculum must be re-visited to ensure overall coherence.\line 2. Module outlines provided are incomplete as they indicate little attention to the level of required achievement in the outcome\'2C to the extent that many \'E2\'80\'98outlines\'27 amount to statements of topics. In some learning areas\'2C the progression of learning is not evident. Consequently\'2C the purpose of the qualification is likely to be compromised.\line 3. No assessment criteria can be identified for all modules in the application. A case in point is the construction of work-based learning which provides experience without explicitly indicating how these experiences are linked to conceptual development. Assessment criteria for work-based learning appear not to have been considered in Programme Design. self-evaluation by students seems to be a main method of evaluation.\line 4. There is inadequate evidence that support and responsibility for the professional growth and development of the large contingent of part-time and independent contractors and support staff is available.\line 5. More information is required to indicate how the apparently relatively small number of full-time staff members will be able to ensure equality of delivery across all sites. Information on the size and capacity of the cohort of administrative staff at sites of delivery is not available.\line 6. More detail on assessment is needed. Assessment tools and method choices are not informed and supported by either the purpose of particular forms of assessment or the criteria for successful achievement. It is necessary that assessment criteria are accompanied by appropriate level descriptor\'28s\'29\'2C and aligned with delivery modes and available resources as well as the chosen assessment methods.\line 7. More information is needed on the availability and access to specialist venues for modules requiring food preparation\'2C food service and cocktail lounge\'2Fbar services. \cell \pard 

