\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator reviewed the additional information together with the original material submitted and found that Criteria 1\'2C 3 and 4 do not comply with minimum standards and that Criteria 2\'2C 5\'2C 6 and 7 are in need of improvement. \line \line In terms of Criterion 1 the main reason for judging this as not compliant with minimum standards is the underdeveloped nature of the 180 hours of WIL. The manner in which the minimum allocation of 180 hours to work-based learning is to be integrated into the revised curriculum is unstated. The evaluator stated that high-level conceptual knowledge of hospitality is linked to practical application. Although useful in teaching and assessment classroom case studies\'2C projects and simulations are very limited in achieving the objective of the programme to provide graduates that think critically and strategically. Against this concern\'2C the programme sets industry exposure at a minimum of 180 hours which is not assessed in the degree. Serious apprehension is raised with respect to the students\'27 ability to cover the entire scope of practical application in this period. Mere industry exposure will not permit practical applications that are basic to hospitality management at the envisaged occupational level.  It is consequently\'2C conceivable that students can obtain a degree without this element regarded by the institution as \'E2\'80\'9Cnecessary for the student to be exposed to the production environments of a hospitality\'E2\'80\'9D.\line \line The curriculum is also seen by the evaluator as problematic. In excess of 50\'25 of the relative weight of the learning area credits leans towards generic studies of management and administration. The introduction of a greater number of credit-bearing learning areas in hospitality specialisms will better align to the qualifier in the qualification.\line \line Another major concern relates to staffing. The highest academic hospitality qualification in the updated list of CVs received is a Diploma held by two academic managers. Moreover\'2C the experience of academic staff in the hospitality vocation is not stated. There is no indication of lecturers with the appropriate occupational qualifications\'2C relevant occupational work experience and industry contacts. Such a situation creates serious difficulties for Institute\'27s efforts to align the programme to sector needs. \line \line Other concerns raised include\'3A\line \'E2\'80\'A2 Rules regarding re-admission\'2C exclusion and envisaged promotion criteria between levels of the programme are not  \line   available\line \'E2\'80\'A2 The updated list of resumes does not include moderators and examiners with an NQF Level 8 \'28or above\'29 qualification in the hospitality vocation.\line \'E2\'80\'A2 The available budget for the specific support and development of teaching is not available.\line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should not be accredited. \line \line \cell \pard 

